        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our main science goal is to image the asymmetric disk around HD 142527 in 13CO and C18O J=1-0 lines and in continuum at 100 GHz. To compare with Band 7 data taken in Cycle 0, we require the same beamsize (0.4") and velocity resolution (0.21 km/s). The largest angular structure is expected to be 6" from the spatial extent of 13CO J=3-2 obtained with Cycle 0 ALMA. 

To obtain the velocity resolution which is the same as Band 7 observations, 13CO and C18O J=1-0 lines are separately included in the two basebands in the upper sideband. We select the correlator mode of 58.594 MHz in bandwidth and 30.518 kHz (corresponding to 0.083 km/s) in smoothed resolution (=2 frequency channel spacings) for these two basebands. We will bind 5 channels to make the velocity resolution to be 0.21 km/s when we make comparison with Band 7 data. The required sensitivity at 0.21 km/s resolution is set to be Tb = 1.25 K (1 sigma) which is identical (in Tb) with our 13CO J=3-2 data in Cycle 0. This corresponds to Tb = 2 K, or 3.2 mJy/beam (0.4" beam) at 0.083 km/s resolution. According to OT, these requirements will be achieved by 5.6-hour integration (or 10.1-hour in total time) even under the moderate atmospheric condition (7th Octile). 

Two basebands will be devoted to the continuum emission at around 100 GHz in lower sideband with 2GHz bandwidth each, and the total bandwidth for the continuum will be 3.9 GHz. The same integration will give us 0.01 mJy beam^{-1}, which is comparable sensitivity in surface density with our Cycle 0 obeservations in Band 7 if dust mass opacity is proportional to the observed frequency. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
